erican Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Massingham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Norfolk): habitational name from Great and Little Massingham (Norfolk). The placenames derive from the Old English personal name <i>Mæssa</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i> (genitive <i>-inga-</i>) + <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Laurence","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a French form of Latin <i>Laurentius</i> ‘man from Laurentum’. <i>Laurentum</i> was a town in Latium, which may have got its name from Latin <i>laurus</i> ‘laurel’, although it is more probably of pre-Roman origin. The given name was moderately popular in the Middle Ages (when it was used for girls as well as boys), under the influence of a 3rd-century saint who was one of the seven deacons of Rome. He was martyred in  258 . The legend is that, having been required to hand over the Church's treasures to the civil authorities, he assembled the poor and sick and presented them. For this act of Christian defiance, he was roasted to death on a gridiron. In England the name is also associated with  St Laurence of Canterbury  (  d. 619 ). A more recent influence has been the actor  Sir Laurence Olivier  (  1907–89 ).  See also  Lawrence ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":4,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705189,"age":39,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705190,"age":70,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Laurence de Massingham was born about 1220, in England. She had at least 1 daughter with Laurence de Massingham, High Sheriff of Huntingdon."},"et":{"about 1220–":"umbes 1220–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1250–1320":"1250–1320","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","1259":"1259","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1320":"1320","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","about 1220":"umbes 1220","1290":"1290","England":"England","Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdonshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1220–":"noin 1220–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1250–1320":"1250–1320","1220–Female":"1220–Kuollut","1259":"1259","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1320":"1320","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","about 1220":"noin 1220","1290":"1290","England":"England","Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdonshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1220–":"environ 1220–Décédée","1200–Male":"1200–Décédé","1250–1320":"1250–1320","1220–Female":"1220–Décédée","1259":"1259","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1320":"1320","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","about 1220":"environ 1220","1290":"1290","England":"Angleterre","Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingd